Multiple Linear Regression

Data set

For this part of the project I will consider the Pima Indians Diabetes Database.

This data set contains 9 variables measured on 392 women of the Pima Indians heritage. The 9 variables are:

  • pregnant: Number of times pregnant

  • glucose: Plasma glucose concentration (glucose tolerance test)

  • pressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)

  • triceps: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)

  • insulin: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml)

  • mass: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)

  • pedigree: Diabetes pedigree function

  • age: Age (years)

  • diabetes: Class variable (test for diabetes)

The aim of this part of the project is to see which variables affect the level of glucose of the patients.First of all, let’s explore the data set by providing a summary of the variables:

PimaIndiansDiabetes2 <- read_excel("PimaIndiansDiabetes2.xlsx")

  mutate(diabetes = ifelse(diabetes=="pos",1,0))
PimaIndiansDiabetes2$diabetes <- as.factor(PimaIndiansDiabetes2$diabetes)
rownames(PimaIndiansDiabetes2)=c(1:nrow(PimaIndiansDiabetes2))

                varnumbers =  FALSE,

Assumptions model 1

I have to check if the classical 7 assumptions of the multiple linear regression are satisfied, otherwise the model is not valid.

1) The regression model is linear in parameters

par(mfrow=c(4,3))
car::crPlots(mod2)

There is a linearity problem because the violet line that models the residuals of the predictor insulin against the dependent variable glucose is not linear as the blue line.

Final Model

The final model is the following:

\[log(glucose) = B_0 + B_1insulin + B_2insulin^2 + B3insulin^3 + B_4age + B_5diabetes + \epsilon \]

It was obtained by removing some outliers and using the logarithm of the dependent variable.

library(jtools)
library(tseries)
library(lmtest)
new_PimaIndiansDiabetes2 <- PimaIndiansDiabetes2[-c(5,19,123,226),]
mod4=lm(log(glucose) ~ poly(insulin,3) + age + diabetes,new_PimaIndiansDiabetes2)
summary(mod4)

All the regressor coefficients are significant at the 5% level of significance. Before checking the assumptions let’s comment the results:

  • The relationship between insulin and glucose is not linear, but is modeled as a 3rd degree polynomial;

  • On average, holding all the other variables constant, for a one-year increase of the age glucose increases by 0.29%;

  • On average, the level of glucose is 100(e^0.14 - 1) = 15% higher in patients who have diabetes than in patients without diabetes.

Moreover, the model is able to capture the 54% of the variability of the phenomenon.

Assumptions final model

Let’s check the assumptions of this model.

1) The regression model is linear in parameters

par(mfrow=c(4,3))
car::crPlots(mod4)

The linearity assumption is satisfied.

2) The mean of residuals is zero and the residuals are normally distributed

mean(mod4$residuals)
## [1] 2.589249e-18

The mean of the residuals is numerically 0.

shapiro.test(mod4$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  mod4$residuals
## W = 0.99823, p-value = 0.9615

The residuals are normally distributed so the assumption is satisfied.

3) Homoscedasticity of residuals

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(mod4)

According to the scale-location plot, residuals seem to be homoscedastic, but let’s conduct a statistical test.

library(skedastic)
gqtest(mod4) 
## 
##  Goldfeld-Quandt test
## 
## data:  mod4
## GQ = 1.1908, df1 = 188, df2 = 188, p-value = 0.1161
## alternative hypothesis: variance increases from segment 1 to 2

According to the Goldfel-Quandt test the homoscedasticity assumption is satisfied.

4) No autocorrelation of residuals

acf(mod4$residuals, type="correlation")

library(lawstat)
lmtest::dwtest(mod4)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  mod4
## DW = 2.1009, p-value = 0.8385
## alternative hypothesis: true autocorrelation is greater than 0

The residuals are not autocorrelated, so the assumption is satisfied.

5) The X variables and residuals are uncorrelated

This assumption is also satisfied, the regressors are exogenous.

6) The number of observations must be greater than the number of predictors

Since there are 388 observations and only 3 independent variables, the assumption is satisfied according to the one in ten rule.

7) Absence of perfect multicollinearity

car::vif(mod4)

The variance inflaction factors of all the variables are < 5, so there is no perfect linear relationship between the predictors and the assumption is satisfied.

Logistic Regression

Let’s now shift the attention on the variables which can influence the probability of having the diabetes.

Model

First of all, let’s consider the full model:

Again, let’s proceed with a backward approach, by iteratively removing the least contributive variables. The final model is the following:

All the predictors are now statistically significant in predicting the logit (the logarithm of the odds for disease) at the 5% significance level. The interpretation in these terms is the following:

  • On average, for a one-unit increase in glucose the logit increases by 0.04, holding all the other variables constant;

  • On average, for a one-unit increase in mass the logit increases by 0.07, holding all the other variables constant;

  • On average, for a one-unit increase in pedigree the logit increases by 1.39, holding all the other variables constant;

  • On average, for a one-unit increase in age the logit increases by 0.05, holding all the other variables constant.

If we want to interpret the results according to probabilities, we have to pass to the exponential transformations of the coefficients:

coefs <- coef(logistic2) # if b was positive, exp(b)>1
(exp(coefs)-1)*100  # percent change in the odds for a one unit increase in the independent variable.
## (Intercept)     glucose        mass    pedigree         age 
##  -99.996219    3.798019    7.270464  341.208878    5.088219

  • For a one-unit increase in glucose, we expect to see a 3.85% increase in the odds of being developing diabetes, keeping constant all the other predictors;

  • For a one-unit increase in mass, we expect to see a 7.3% increase in the odds of being developing diabetes, keeping constant all the other predictors;

  • For a one-unit increase in pedigree, we expect to see a 302% increase in the odds of being developing diabetes, keeping constant all the other predictors;

  • For a one-unit increase in age, we expect to see a 5.344% increase in the odds of being developing diabetes, keeping constant all the other predictors;

library(pscl)
pR2(logistic2)
## fitting null model for pseudo-r2
##          llh      llhNull           G2     McFadden         r2ML         r2CU

The McFadden Pseudo R-squared indicates an excellent model fit since it is in the range 0.2-0.4.

Assumptions

Let’s check the assumptions of the logistic regression.

1) The observations are independent of each other

This assumption is satisfied because the observations do not come from repeated measurement. Each statistical unit is a different woman.

2) No high multicollinearity between the independent variables

car::vif(logistic2)
##  glucose     mass pedigree      age 
## 1.044599 1.012483 1.022934 1.035123

The variance inflaction factors are < 5 for all the independent variables, so multicollinearity is absent.

3) Linear relationship between independent variables and logit

To check this assumption, first of all I compute the predicted probabilities of diabete positivity

# Predict the probability (p) of diabete positivity
probabilities <- predict(logistic2, type = "response")
predicted.classes <- ifelse(probabilities > 0.5, "pos", "neg")
head(predicted.classes)
##     1     2     3     4     5     6 
## "neg" "neg" "neg" "pos" "pos" "pos"
# Select only numeric predictors
mydata <- PimaIndiansDiabetes2 %>%
  dplyr::select(glucose, mass, pedigree, age) 
predictors <- colnames(mydata) # names of the predictors
# Bind the logit and tidying the data for doing the plot
mydata <- mydata %>%
  mutate(logit = log(probabilities/(1-probabilities))) %>%
  gather(key = "predictors", value = "predictor.value", -logit)
ggplot(mydata, aes(logit, predictor.value))+
  geom_point(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  facet_wrap(~predictors, scales = "free_y")

The linearity assumption is more or less satisfied.

4) Large sample size

This assumption is also satisfied because we have at least 10 observations per predictor.

Influential values

Finally, let’s check if there are some influential observations. (according to the Cook’s distance).

plot(logistic2, which = 4, id.n = 3)

Not all outliers are influential observations. To check whether the data contains potential influential observations, the standardized residual error can be inspected. Data points with an absolute standardized residuals above 3 represent possible influential observations and may deserve closer attention.

# Extract model results
library(broom)
model.data <- augment(logistic2) %>% 
  mutate(index = 1:n())
ggplot(model.data, aes(index, .std.resid)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = diabetes), alpha = .5) +
  theme_bw()

model.data %>% 
  filter(abs(.std.resid) > 3)

Unsupervised classification

Data set

For this part of the project I will consider a data set about the quality of life in different countries.

In particular, this data set contains 10 variables measured on 96 countries. The variables are:

  • country: name of the country;

  • child_mort: mortality rate of children under the age of five;

  • exports: ialue of the exports (in billions);

  • health: index that measures the extent to which people in a country are healthy and have access to the necessary services to maintain good health;

  • imports: value of the imports (in billions);

  • income: mean income ($);

  • inflation: inflation rate;

  • total_fer: fertility rate;

  • gdpp: gross domestic product per capita ($).

To perform unsupervised classification let’s normalize the variables to remove the effects of different ranges of variation.

country_data <- country_data %>%
  select_if(is.numeric)
normalize <- function(x){
  return ((x-min(x))/(max(x)-min(x)))
}
country_data <- as.data.frame(lapply(country_data,normalize))
country_data1 <- read_excel("country_data.xlsx")
rownames(country_data)=country_data1$country

Agglomerative hierarchical clustering

From the results it’s clear that the best approach is to use agglomerative hierarchical clustering with 2 clusters.

# euclidean - complete linkage
dd=dist(country_data, method = "euclidean") # 2 variables because I want to plot the groups
library(dendextend)
clusters = hclust(dd,method = "complete")
cut = cutree(clusters, 2)
dend <- as.dendrogram(clusters)
dend <- color_branches(dend, k=2)
circlize_dendrogram(dend, labels = TRUE)

To interpret the results, let’s perform a principal component analysis.

Principal Component Analysis

library(factoextra)
fviz_cluster(list(data = country_data, cluster = cut))

Let’s see which are the variables that influence the principal components

library(gridExtra)
res.pca <- prcomp(country_data, scale = TRUE)
fviz_pca_var(res.pca, scale = TRUE)

p1 <- fviz_contrib(res.pca, choice="var", axes=1, fill="pink", color="grey", top=10)
p2 <- fviz_contrib(res.pca, choice="var", axes=2, fill="skyblue", color="grey", top=10)
grid.arrange(p1,p2,ncol=2)

The first principal component is determined by variables related to the quality of life (life_expect, child_mort, total_fert, income) while the second principal component is determined more by economic variables (imports and exports). So we can easily understand that the blue cluster is made by advanced economies and “civilized” countries (incomes, life expectancy and gdp above the average, child mortality below the average), while the red cluster is made by poor countries (income, gpd and life expectancy below the average, child mortality above the average), in which there are wars and in which the quality of life is not high.

Supervised classification

Data set

In this last section of the project, I will consider a data set about the characteristics of two types of wines produced in Portugal.

In particular, this data set contains 13 variables measured on 6463 wines. The variables are:

  • type: type of the wine (red or white);

  • fixed_acidity: difference between total acidity and volatile acidity (mg/L);

  • volatile_acidity: steam distillable acids present in wine (mg/L);

  • citric_acid: quantity of acidification to boost the wine’s total acidity (g);

  • residual_sugar: sugar left unfermented in a finished wine (g/L);

  • chlorides: indicative of the presence of sodium chloride 5 Sodium chloride adds to the saltiness of a wine, which can contribute to or detract from the overall taste and quality of the wine (mg/L);

  • free_sulfur_dioxide: gives anti-oxidative and anti-microbial properties to wine (ppm);

  • total_sulfur_dioxide: portion of SO2 that is free in the wine plus the portion that is bound to other chemicals in the wine such as aldehydes, pigments, or sugars (mg/L);

  • density: ratio between mass and volume (g/cm3);

  • pH: measure of the acidity of wine;

  • suplhates: give antioxidant and antibacterial action to wine (mg/L);

  • alcohol: percentage of alcohol present;

  • quality: quality of the wine (1=poor, 10=excellent)

Let’s explore the data set by providing a summary of the variables:

K-Nearest Neighbors

Let’s perform classification using the k-nearest neighbors algorithm. In this case k = 7.

library(class)
random<- sample(rep(1:6463)) # randomly generate numbers from 1 to 150
winequalityN<- winequalityN[random,] # randomize "winequalityN" 
normalize <- function(x){
  return ((x-min(x))/(max(x)-min(x)))
}
winequalityN.new<- as.data.frame(lapply(winequalityN[,c(2:13)],normalize))

winequalityN.train<- winequalityN.new[1:4308,]
winequalityN.train.label<- winequalityN[1:4308,1]
winequalityN.test<- winequalityN.new[4309:6463,]
winequalityN.test.label<- winequalityN[4309:6463,1]
set.seed(2)
predict <- knn(train=winequalityN.train, test=winequalityN.test, cl=winequalityN.train.label, k=7)
table <- table(winequalityN.test.label, predict)
table
##                        predict
## winequalityN.test.label  red white
##                   red    518     9
##                   white    9  1619

Choosing 7 neighbors, only 18 wines out of 2155 were not classified in the correct group, so the misclassification error rate is very low. In particular, let’s see its plot in function of k (the number of neighbors):

err=length(winequalityN.test.label)-sum(winequalityN.test.label==predict)
error_rate=err/length(predict)
res=rep(NA,20)
for(i in 1:20){mod=knn(train=winequalityN.train, test=winequalityN.test, cl=winequalityN.train.label, k=i)
          acc=sum(winequalityN.test.label==mod)
          res[i]=1-acc/length(mod)}
plot(1:20,res,type="l",col="red", xlab="Neighbours", ylab="Misclassification error rate")

We can see that with k = 8 the misclassification error rate is lowert than 0.0085 and it is the minimum while increasing the number of neighbors the misclassification error rate increases too.

Since we are dealing with a binary classifier, we can also plot the ROC curve and talk about sensityivity and specifity.

library(psych)
psych::AUC(table, plot = "a")

In this case, sensitivity is the proportion of actually red wines classified as red wines (actual positive classified as positive) while specifity is the proportion of actually white wines classified as white wines. They are both very high.

This also proves that the classifier is almost perfect because the area under the curve is almost 1.

Note: specifity is 1 only because of approximation. The real value is (1633/(1633+5)) = 0.997
